{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BAKd4fh9zsWfjMmggZc9Jp","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story status updated to `verifying`.\n\n---\n\n## Adversarial Code Review Summary\n\n**Story:** 12-2 OpenCode Driver Implementation\n**Files reviewed:** `opencode.ts` (339 lines), `opencode-driver.test.ts` (720 lines), `index.ts` barrel export, 5 fixture files\n**Reference compared:** `codex.ts`, `codex-driver.test.ts`, `types.ts`, `stream-parser.ts`\n\n**HIGH issues found:** 0\n**MEDIUM issues found:** 0\n\n**Build:** Passes (zero TypeScript errors)\n**Tests:** 64/64 pass\n**Coverage:** 96.78% overall (above 90% target), all 169 files above 80% per-file floor\n\nThe implementation is a correct structural adaptation of the CodexDriver with all documented OpenCode-specific differences properly applied: `supportsPlugins: true`, `--plugin` flag pass-through, `defaultModel = 'default'`, correct binary name and install URL. Error classification, cost handling, timeout, result guarantee, and streaming logic are all correct.\n\n---\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found:** None.\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- Duplicated `classifyError()` and `parseLine()` functions between `codex.ts` and `opencode.ts` (~80 identical lines each). Architecture explicitly requires this (self-contained driver files), so it's intentional tech debt. If a third CLI-wrapped driver is added, consider extracting a shared `cli-driver-utils.ts`.\n- `console.debug` used for unparseable line logging — no structured logger. Both drivers share this pattern. Fine for now, but a structured logger would be better for production use.\n- Fixture `.txt` files in `test/fixtures/drivers/opencode/` are not used by the test file — tests use inline fixture data instead. The files exist but are dead artifacts.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- No integration tests against a real `opencode` binary (expected — binary is not available in CI).\n- No test for concurrent dispatches on the same driver instance (potential `lastCost` race, but `dispatch` is async generator so practically serial per consumer).\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- None. Pattern matches the established driver architecture exactly.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 12\n- By tool: Bash: 3, Read: 7, Edit: 1, Grep: 1, Glob: 3, Skill: 1, Write: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `codeharness coverage` (~7 lines), `vitest run` (~8 lines), `npm run build` (~5 lines)\n- Files read: 8 unique, 8 total reads (no file read more than once)\n- Redundant operations: None. The Glob search for `*code-review*` was a necessary exploration to find the missing workflow file."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1531aa305969fb46 (use SendMessage with to: 'a1531aa305969fb46' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 57142\ntool_uses: 18\nduration_ms: 99615</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"65932dfc-6881-4906-8881-56eaa8ade510","uuid":"5899c2ba-a771-49e6-9111-ead7b4d2c8e0","timestamp":"2026-04-03T09:28:29.157Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/12-2-opencode-driver-implementation.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas ne